> >
> > can also get a large C clamp in there useing the old pad to keep from
> > scatching the piston or can also break down and get the right tool
> from
> > sears or harbor frt. ; )
> > Chuck
> > ----- Original Message -----
> > From: "Mike Benthin" <benthin_at_prodigy_dot_net>
> > To: "Phillip Rose" <phillip_at_technostate_dot_com>
> > Cc: <type2_at_type2_dot_com>
> > Sent: Friday, March 29, 2002 10:32 AM
> > Subject: [T2] Re: Moving the piston in disk brake
> >
> >
> > > Don't bother with the bleeder bolt - I wedge the caliper piston back
> > by
> > > prying between the rotor disk and the piston.  I cut a piece of 2x4
> > into a
> > > wedge shape (chop saw) so I can wedge it between the opposite
> > piston/rotor
> > > space, to prevent a possibility of warping the rotor disk.  Then
> wedge
> > the
> > > piston in with a "pickle fork" or tie rod separator or a small pry
> bar
> > > levered against the rotor with a piece of leather or such to prevent
> > > scratching the disk.  I think I've done it with another piecer of
> 2x4
> > > thinned at the end to get in there and wedge back the piston.  You
> > need
> > > about a foot or more of leverage.  Make sure you didn't just top up
> > the
> > > fluid resorvoir, or it will go above the vent hole and soak the
> > surrounding
> > > body.
> > > >>I can't get the "I
> > > > don't know what it is called" to compress.  Does anyone have any
> > > > suggestions as to what I can do to get this job done Thanks for
> your
> > > > time.
> > > >
> > > >
> > > > Phillip
> > >
> > >
> > >
> > ></pre>


